19:59.198 --> 20:02.368 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
thanks so much.

20:02.468 --> 20:06.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SUSAN PAGE: Thank you.

20:06.772 --> 20:10.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
REID WILSON: Thank you.

20:11.077 --> 20:17.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Five years ago
today, Egypt
stood at the edge of tectonic
changes. The

20:17.116 --> 20:23.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
protests that began January 25,
2011, in Cairo's
Tahrir Square would soon cause
the military-led

20:23.456 --> 20:26.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ouster of longtime President
Hosni Mubarak.

20:26.859 --> 20:31.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the culmination of the
so-called 18
days, and a high point of what
became known

20:31.297 --> 20:38.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as the Arab Spring. In 2012,
Egyptians elected
Mohammed Morsi of the Muslim
Brotherhood president.

20:38.537 --> 20:44.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The next year, he was deposed by
the military
and its top general, Abdel
Fattah El-Sisi.

20:44.844 --> 20:47.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sisi was then elected president
in 2014.

20:47.813 --> 20:53.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It has been five years of
upheaval and tumult.
And, today, the picture from
Cairo is much

20:53.519 --> 20:56.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
changed from those days of
protest.

20:56.722 --> 21:00.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Nick
Schifrin begins
tonight our series of three
reports, 5 Years

21:01.093 --> 21:02.428 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
On.

21:02.528 --> 21:06.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Take me back five
years ago.

21:06.398 --> 21:11.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: We kept crying from
happiness. I couldn't
believe it, we were saying. We
did it. We

21:11.470 --> 21:14.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
made it. It was a dream that
came true.

21:14.940 --> 21:17.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: All Egyptians are happy.

21:17.810 --> 21:25.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I
cried. I cried.
I was ecstatic. We laughed,
jumped, hugged

21:25.851 --> 21:29.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
my colleagues, shouted. We did
everything.

21:29.321 --> 21:34.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: How exciting was
that time?

21:34.193 --> 21:36.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): After
the revolution,
we felt the highest stage of
freedom and expression

21:36.962 --> 21:39.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in our lives.

21:40.032 --> 21:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Five years later,
the revolution's
protagonists still revel in 18
days they call

21:50.543 --> 21:59.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
utopia. But, today, the square
that toppled
a dictator is empty. There are
no celebrations

21:59.552 --> 22:02.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and no protesters, because
protests are illegal.

22:02.288 --> 22:08.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMAL SHARAF, April 6 Movement:
During Mubarak,
at least we had the chance to
speak. Now we

22:08.260 --> 22:18.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are ruled by weapons. We can't
open our mouths.
If you go into the street, you
can get shot.

22:18.671 --> 22:24.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Today, Egypt is
tense. Above
Cairo's streets, President Abdel
Fattah El-Sisi

22:24.643 --> 22:29.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and his government keep a close
watch. They
have forcibly muted almost all
opposition.

22:30.049 --> 22:36.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When a state TV anchor
criticized him, she
was suspended. When a comedian
spoofed police

22:36.388 --> 22:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
