against them are settled. The
coal industry

40:45.076 --> 40:48.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and a consortium of states have
sued to stop
the rules, calling them -- quote
-- "a power

40:49.047 --> 40:50.848 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
grab."

40:50.948 --> 40:53.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help us understand all this,
we turn to
Coral Davenport, who has been
reporting the

40:53.217 --> 40:54.919 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
story for The New York Times.

40:55.019 --> 40:59.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Coral, before we get to what
the court
ordered, let's talk a little bit
about these

40:59.557 --> 41:03.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
regulations. These are not some
arcane set
of rules. These seem pretty
fundamental to

41:03.161 --> 41:05.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the president's environmental
agenda.

41:05.129 --> 41:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CORAL DAVENPORT, The New York
Times: Yes,
the regulation that was put on
hold is really

41:09.801 --> 41:13.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
at the heart of President
Obama's climate
change agenda.

41:13.404 --> 41:18.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In his second term, President
Obama really
wanted to build a legacy around
addressing

41:18.343 --> 41:24.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
climate change. He just got back
less than
two months ago from a meeting in
Paris where

41:24.949 --> 41:30.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
